Performance tiers — when to use each.

Let's tie the whole module together into one decision you can carry to every problem. The question is always the same — what is the fastest tool that can express this logic? Work down the tiers from fast to slow, and stop at the first one that fits.

Tier one, and your default, is the built-in function library. String work, date work, array work, conditionals, numeric helpers — all of it compiles through Tungsten with no serialization. This is as fast as Spark gets.

Tier two, for element-wise work inside arrays and maps, is the higher-order functions. Their lambdas run on the java virtual machine, so they stay fast.

Tier three, when you genuinely need numpy, pandas, or scikit-learn, is the pandas user-defined function — series to series for row-wise work, the iterator variant when you have expensive one-time setup, and apply-in-pandas for custom group-level logic that needs a full pandas dataframe.

And the bottom tier is the plain Python user-defined function. It is acceptable for simple custom logic on small data when nothing else fits. But on billions of rows it is ten to a hundred times slower and it pressures the garbage collector, so rewrite it as built-ins or a pandas function before it reaches a hot path.

The instinct to internalize — never start at the bottom. Start at the top and only descend when you must.
